Feature: Replace compiler.coordinate special-case with abstract/impl

The current approach uses a hack:
- compiler.coordinate is intentionally left unimplemented
- compiler.coordinate.default has the actual pipeline
- main.zig bootstrap logic falls back to .default

The proper solution uses Koru's abstract/impl feature (see test 210_015):

```koru
// In koru_std/compiler.kz:
~abstract pub event compiler.coordinate { program_ast: *const Program, allocator: std.mem.Allocator }
| coordinated { ast: *const Program, code: []const u8, metrics: []const u8 }
| error { message: []const u8 }

// Default subflow implementation (same file, no ~impl keyword)
~compiler.coordinate =
    compiler.context.create(program_ast: program_ast, allocator: allocator)
    | created c0 |> compiler.coordinate.frontend(ctx: c0.ctx)
      | continued c1 |> compiler.coordinate.transform_taps(ctx: c1.ctx)
        | continued c2 |> compiler.coordinate.analysis(ctx: c2.ctx)
          | continued c3 |> compiler.coordinate.test_generation(ctx: c3.ctx)
            | continued c4 |> compiler.coordinate.optimize(ctx: c4.ctx)
              | continued c5 |> compiler.coordinate.emission(ctx: c5.ctx)
                | continued c6 |> coordinated { ... }
          | failed f |> error { message: f.message }
```

User override (in user code):
```koru
~impl compiler.coordinate =
    // Custom pipeline - can delegate to default via compiler.coordinate(...)
    compiler.coordinate(program_ast: program_ast, allocator: allocator)
    | coordinated c |> // ... extend or wrap ...
```

This removes:
1. The compiler.coordinate.default indirection
2. Special bootstrap logic in main.zig
3. The "intentionally unimplemented" hack

Benefits:
- Uses standard abstract/impl machinery (validate_abstract_impl.zig)
- Consistent with how other extensibility works in Koru
- Explicit delegation (not hidden like OOP super())
- Single implementation enforced at compile time
